	<table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0">
	
	<tr>
	
		<td width="18"><img src="/Graphics/Interface/Icons/spacer.gif" width=18 height=1 border=0></td>
	
	
		<td>
	




	<font size="-1"><b>Cisco, Microsoft, Nortel, PSINet Headline Speaker Line-up</b></font>

	<p>Arlington, VA - Nov, 29 1999
	<BR>
	As the showcase for the who, what, where and why of buying and selling, the <b>2000 International CES - Your Source for Workstyle and Lifestyle Technology</b>, will spotlight the foremost industry and government leaders involved in developing the online marketplace.  Top executives from Cisco, CNET, Cyberian Outpost, Microsoft, Nortel, PSINet, and other Internet leaders will headline more than a dozen e-commerce-focused conference sessions at CES, to be held in Las Vegas, January 6-9, 2000. <P>
 "At CES, industry visionaries illustrate new business models made possible by technology.  With the success of e-commerce sites like Amazon.com and others, it is imperative for brick-and-mortar stores to learn about the business models being used on the Web and how to use the Web to enhance their retail operations," said Robbi Lycett, CES vice president. "CES offers numerous opportunities for executives to network and learn about e-commerce opportunities with our conference tracks, supersession, and exhibits."  <P>
 <b>Internet 2000</b><br> On Friday, January 7, <b>Virginia Governor James Gilmore</b>, chairman of the Advisory Commission on E-Commerce, hosts and leads a half-day summit on the Internet's impact on American society in the new millennium.  Key state governors, technology leaders and government officials discuss the Internet's global impact and how government and business can work together to enhance the opportunities created by the Internet.   <P>
 <b>Bill Schrader, CEO, PSINet</b>, will give the opening keynote address, followed by a high-level discussion on taxation, encryption and privacy on the Internet with presentations by Gilmore; <b>Rep. Thomas Bliley (R-Va.)</b>, chairman of the House Commerce Committee; and <b>Brad Chase, senior vice president of e-commerce, Microsoft Corp.</b>  Then, several top industry executives present their views on Internet infrastructure, workforce challenges and commerce, including <b>John Chambers, CEO, Cisco Systems;</b> and <b>John Roth, chairman, Nortel Networks</b>.  The program is open to all attendees and takes place in the Las Vegas Hilton Theater. <P>
 <b>CES E-Commerce Supersession and Conference Track</b><br> In the CES E-Commerce Supersession, to be held at 4:30pm on Friday, January 7 in the Las Vegas Hilton Theater, hear from online experts, including: <b>Darryl Peck, chairman, Cyberian Outpost; Henry Chiarelli, executive vice president, RadioShack.com; Kevin McKenzie, vice president, CNET Inc.</b>; and <b>Suresh Shenoy, executive vice president, Information Management Consultants Inc.</b> <P>
 In six sessions, the CES comprehensive e-commerce conference track examines the new world of business on the Internet, covering Internet retailing, the basics of e-commerce, the role of TV-based e-commerce, online privacy concerns and using the Internet as a business strategy.  Speakers include representatives from Associated Volume Buyers, Cameraworld.com, Chumbo.com, Electonics.net, The Fantastic Corp., IBM, Marketingweb.com, Modem Media.Poppe Tyson, NPD Intelect, OneChannel.net, QVC Interactive, Roxy.com, and USAToday.com.  Plus, one session sponsored by <i>Yahoo! Internet Life</i> covers "Selling Consumer Electronics on the Net: What Works and What Doesn't" with panelists from 800.com and Sony. <P>
 CES also has 11 other e-commerce-related conference sessions for retailers, industry executives and content developers.  Speakers include representatives from ActiveWorlds, Avenue A Internet Media, Art Technology Group, BigStar Entertainment, Blaxxun Interactive, Blue Barn Interactive, Brandwise.com, Brilliant Media, Buena Vista Internet Group, CheckOut.com, Comet Systems, CustomDisc.com, Cyber Dialogue, Cyberworld International, Enews.com, FamilyWonder.com, Giant Step, iBelong, IBM, Infoseek, Interactive Bureau, Kesmai Corp., L90, MathEngine, MusicChoice, NetZero, Reel.com, Siggraph-Los Angeles, Silknet Software, WebTV Networks and Younology. <P>
 <b>E-Commerce Exhibits</b><br> Beyond the conference sessions, CES attendees can see the newest e-commerce technologies and applications on the show floor from exhibitors such as America Online and Excalibur.  The CES <b>E-Commerce Pavilion</b> in the North Hall of the Las Vegas Convention Center also features exhibits from Assist Corner, Audiocafe.com, CDS Solutions Group, Click Move, Electronics Partner, GetPlugged.com, Infomatec, International Management Consultants Inc., Roxy.com, Tradeout.com, Xpedior and Weaver Corp. <P>
 The Consumer Electronics Association (CEA) is a sector of the Electronic Industries Alliance (EIA), the 75-year-old Arlington, Virginia-based trade organization representing all facets of electronics manufacturing.  CEA represents more than 500 U.S. manufacturers of audio, video, accessories, mobile electronics, communication, information technology and multimedia products that are sold through consumer channels.   <P>
 As the sponsor, manager and producer of the International CES-Your Source for Workstyle and Lifestyle Technology, CEA reinvests all profits from CES into industry services, including technical training and education, product promotion, engineering standards development, market research, and governmental and legal affairs support.  As the first major technology event of the new millennium, the 2000 International CES is the launch pad for 21st century technology.  <P>
 <i>The last two pages of this press release contain an E-Commerce Fact Sheet that could not be uploaded to the Internet. For a faxed copy, please call Julie Severson at 703 907 7041</i>.  <P>
